Of the 26 unexpected fails remaining on 3.2.3, the first is
gcc.c-torture/compile/20010227-1.c.  I freely admit that I don't know what the
hell I'm doing, but bisecting finds git commit:

26a7cedebb71587b1391f81842c9c86d4c07c061

git-svn-id: svn+ssh://gcc.gnu.org/svn/gcc/trunk@58774
138bc75d-0d04-0410-961f-82ee72b054a4

The changes introduced by this commit seem extremely relevant to the problem,
which is surprising.  The failure is not an expected failure, so presumably
back in the day it passed.  If it passed then and failed now I would expect the
more recent failure of the test to be a weird subtle effect of the modern build
environment through the stages of bootstrap.  Instead we see a change which
appears to address exactly the thing that happened, which I would have only
expected if the test was failing originally.  Like I said, I don't know what
I'm doing so I'm probably just being dumb here.

Decided to patch it anyway since it probably only changes behaviour from "die"
to something else, rather than changing existing code generation.

Eliminated 5 fails on the 3.2 branch.  21 to go on 3.2.3.

